            <tr>
              <td colspan="7">
                <p class="ia-table-text"><b>What is the problem under consideration? Why is government intervention necessary?</b></p>
                <p class="ia-table-text">In the UK, an estimated 100,000 babies are admitted to neonatal care each year following their birth. Many of these babies spend prolonged periods of time in neonatal care as a result of being born prematurely, with congenital conditions, complications at birth, or experiencing serious health conditions shortly after birth. During this time parents face significant practical considerations in order to spend time with their new baby (or babies). Currently, parents in these circumstances rely on their statutory leave entitlements which means a considerable proportion of their leave may be used while the baby in still hospital. The Government proposes a Neonatal Care Leave and Pay entitlement to replace the number of weeks their child spends in neonatal care (up to a maximum of 12) so parents can spend time caring for their child outside of a medical environment.</p>
                <p class="ia-table-text" />
