      <level>
        <content>
          <p><i><u>Deadweight Costs</u></i></p>
        </content>
      </level>
      <paragraph>
        <num>81.</num>
        <intro>
          <p>Deadweight refers to outcomes that occur without Government intervention. Within the context of this policy, deadweight could arise because:</p>
        </intro>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Some employers already provide a comparable leave entitlement to parents who are affected by their child spending prolonged periods of time in neonatal care i.e., “compassionate leave” or “special leave”.</p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Some employers provide paid leave to employees affected by the circumstances outlined above either at or beyond the statutory rate. </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
        <subparagraph>
          <num>3.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Employees use other forms of leave (annual leave) </p>
          </content>
        </subparagraph>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>82.</num>
        <content>
          <p>In these circumstances, the introduction of the policy would not yield an additional cost to employers who were already providing a comparable right to Neonatal Leave and Pay but it would mean employers could reclaim the costs of Statutory Pay from the Exchequer. This would mean costs are transferred from business to the Exchequer with no additional benefit in terms of individuals taking neonatal leave. Furthermore, these benefits which accrue from Neonatal Leave and Pay will not be additional if employees use annual leave instead of this entitlement. Parents might have a preference to use annual leave as it is paid at full rate. Therefore, there is a financial disincentive to use Neonatal Leave and Pay over annual leave. However, employees have a finite amount of annual leave and requests can be delayed by the employer so Annual Leave may not be utilised. </p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <paragraph>
        <num>83.</num>
        <content>
          <p>We have assumed that all costs generated by the proposal would be additional, that is, there would be no deadweight costs. The Carer’s Leave Impact Assessment states that 39% of businesses offer 4-6 days of paid compassionate leave. This policy gives parents the right to take up to 12 weeks paid leave in addition to any maternity or paternity leave that might have been taken and therefore it is unlikely that businesses routinely offer extended periods of paid leave. Furthermore, employers may not recognise the need to offer additional leave to parents of babies in neonatal care, as they assume that Maternity and Paternity Leave is sufficient.</p>
        </content>
      </paragraph>
      <level>
        <content>
          <p><b>Costs to the Exchequer</b></p>
        </content>
      </level>
